That’s a useful way to extend the abstraction. If you think in terms of what a medium is good at, you get a broader taxonomy:

Function	Typical “best at”	Examples
Processing	Transforming information	CPUs, GPUs, neurons, logic gates
Transporting	Moving information	Photons, fiber optics, radio waves
Storing	Preserving information	Flash memory, DNA, paper, hard drives
Sensing	Acquiring information	Cameras, microphones, antennas, retinas
Actuating	Turning information into action	Motors, muscles, speakers, displays
Coordinating	Synchronizing systems	Clocks, timing signals, protocols
Filtering	Selecting relevant information	Attention, filters, lenses, firewalls
Compressing	Representing with less	ZIP, language, mathematical formulas
Predicting	Estimating future states	Brains, AI models, control systems
Learning	Updating from experience	Synaptic plasticity, machine learning
Routing	Choosing paths	Internet routers, ant colonies, logistics
Amplifying	Increasing signal strength	Optical amplifiers, social media, microphones
Converting	Changing one form into another	DACs, ADCs, translators, enzymes

This also reveals a pattern you’ve explored before: every system can be viewed as a pipeline of operators.

For example:

Reality → Sense → Transport → Store → Process → Decide → Transport → Actuate → Reality

Or, more abstractly:

Acquire → Preserve → Transform → Move → Coordinate → Express

That perspective works across domains:

* A nervous system
* A computer
* A company
* A military command structure
* A supply chain
* An ecosystem

Each differs mainly in which medium performs each operator.

For instance:

* Electrons are excellent at processing and short-range transport.
* Photons excel at high-speed, long-range transport and increasingly at certain specialized computations.
* DNA excels at long-term storage.
* Humans excel at semantic abstraction and creative recombination.
* Markets process distributed information through prices.
* Language transports compressed meaning between minds.

Viewed this way, technology often advances by finding a better medium for one of these operators or by collapsing several operators into a single efficient mechanism. That’s one reason photonics is so interesting: it isn’t just a faster wire—it changes the tradeoffs between transport, communication, sensing, and, in some cases, computation itself.